06624nam a22007935i 9780773590465DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735904657 a10.1515/97807735904652doi  a(DE-B1597)655987  a(OCoLC)872944573  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0490002bisacsh04aC815 .42231 aHansen, Hans V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRiel's Defence :bPerspectives on His Speeches /cHans V. Hansen. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPreface to the Texts of Louis Riel’s Addresses to the Jury and the Court -- tLouis Riel’s Address to the Jury, 31 July 1885 -- tLouis Riel’s Address to the Court, 1 August 1885 -- tThe Queen vs Louis Riel: The Historical Context -- t“Through the Grace of God I Am the Founder of Manitoba”: Louis Riel’s Constitutional Thought -- tLouis Riel’s Trial Speeches -- tThe Use and Force of Rhetorical Strategies in Louis Riel’s First Speech -- tNarrative and Logical Orders in Louis Riel’s Address to the Jury -- t“A New German-Indian World” in the North-West: A Métis Deconstruction of the Rhetoric of Immigration in Louis Riel’s Trial Speeches -- tReconstructing the Substantive Argument in Louis Riel’s Address to the Jury -- t“An Insane and Irresponsible Government”: Louis Riel and the Representation of Responsibility -- t“Who Starts the Nations?” Louis Riel and the Question of Geopolitical Legitimacy -- tLouis Riel’s Ethos and the Différend -- tThe Case of Two Trials, Louis Riel and Socrates: Intersections, Overlaps, Divergences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1885, Louis Riel was charged with high treason, found guilty, and consequently executed for his role in Saskatchewan's North-West Rebellion. During his trial, the Métis leader gave two speeches, passionately defending the interests of the Métis in western Canada as well as his own life. Riel's Defence studies these speeches, demonstrating the range of Riel's political and personal concerns. The first and better known of the two speeches addresses the jury, while Riel's second speech - rarely reprinted - addresses the court following his guilty verdict. Both orations have been edited, annotated, and reprinted, and are followed by essays from diverse perspectives including philosophy, law, history, political science, religion, and communication studies. Through the course of their inquiry, contributors come to understand more about Riel's personal character and political thought, as well as his arguments supporting Métis land claims, grievances against the federal government, and his immigration plan for the North-West. Evaluating the rhetorical quality, legal merit, and cultural stakes of his speeches, Riel's Defence reveals the significance of the last public statements made by a man who indelibly shaped Canada’s history by combining his personal vision with a national vision.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aForensic orationsxHistoryx19th centuryxCanada, Western. 0aForensic orationszCanada, WesternxHistoryy19th century. 0aMétisxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada, WesternxHistoryy19th century. 0aMétisxLegal status, laws, etcxHistoryx19th centuryxCanada, Western. 0aMétisxLegal status, laws, etczCanada, WesternxHistoryy19th century. 0aNorthwest Resistance, Canada, 1885vSources. 0aRhetoricxHistoryx19th centuryxCanada, Western. 0aRhetoriczCanada, WesternxHistoryy19th century. 0aRiel Rebellion, 1885vSources. 0aRiel Reb